<body>
  <div class="container">
    <h1>Body Fat Percentage Calculator</h1>
    <p style="text-align:center; margin-bottom:2rem">
      This free body fat calculator estimates your body fat percentage using the U.S. Navy Method ‚Äî a trusted formula based on your gender, height, neck, waist, and hip measurements. More accurate than BMI, it's ideal for tracking fitness, building muscle, or planning weight loss.
    </p>

    <label for="gender">Gender</label>
    <select id="gender">
      <option value="male">Male</option>
      <option value="female">Female</option>
    </select>

    <label for="height">Height (in inches)</label>
    <input type="number" id="height" placeholder="e.g. 70" />

    <label for="neck">Neck Circumference (in inches)</label>
    <input type="number" id="neck" placeholder="e.g. 15.5" />

    <label for="waist">Waist Circumference (in inches)</label>
    <input type="number" id="waist" placeholder="e.g. 34.5" />

    <label for="hip" id="hipLabel" style="display:none;">Hip Circumference (in inches)</label>
    <input type="number" id="hip" placeholder="e.g. 38.5" style="display:none;" />

    <button onclick="calculateBodyFat()">Calculate Body Fat %</button>

    <div class="result" id="bfResult"></div>

    <div class="faq">
      <h2>üìò FAQ: Understanding Body Fat, Accuracy, and Health</h2>
      <p><strong>Is body fat calculation the same as BMI?</strong><br>
      No! BMI only uses height and weight. Body fat percentage estimates your actual fat content using measurements, making it more reliable for fitness goals.</p>

      <p><strong>What‚Äôs a healthy body fat percentage?</strong><br>
      Men: 10‚Äì20%. Women: 18‚Äì28%. Athletes can go lower, but everyone is different. Use this as a guideline.</p>

      <p><strong>Can I use this to track weight loss?</strong><br>
      Absolutely. It‚Äôs great for tracking fat loss, which is more important than scale weight alone.</p>

      <p><strong>Why measure waist, neck, and hips?</strong><br>
      These areas indicate fat storage. The Navy formula uses them to estimate your fat more precisely.</p>

      <p><strong>Why does it ask for hips for women?</strong><br>
      Women tend to store fat in the hips. It improves accuracy of the body fat estimate.</p>

      <p><strong>How accurate is it?</strong><br>
      It‚Äôs a strong estimate. Not perfect like DEXA scans, but great for daily fitness tracking.</p>

      <p><strong>What if I‚Äôm over 30%?</strong><br>
      That‚Äôs considered high. It‚Äôs a signal to consider diet, activity, or medical guidance. No shame ‚Äî just awareness.</p>

      <p><strong>Is this better than scale weight?</strong><br>
      Yes. Two people may weigh the same but have different body fat percentages ‚Äî body fat reveals much more.</p>

      <p><strong>How should I measure?</strong><br>
      Use soft measuring tape. Measure waist at belly button, hips at widest point, and neck below the larynx.</p>

      <p><strong>Can kids use this?</strong><br>
      No. This tool is meant for adults. Kids need age-specific charts.</p>

      <p><strong>How often should I check?</strong><br>
      Every 1‚Äì2 weeks. Avoid obsessing daily. Track trends instead.</p>

      <p><strong>Will lifting weights affect my body fat?</strong><br>
      Yes! You might lose fat while gaining muscle ‚Äî that‚Äôs why body fat is a better metric than the scale.</p>

      <p><strong>What‚Äôs a typical athletic range?</strong><br>
      Men: 6‚Äì13%. Women: 14‚Äì20%. Staying in this range often means strong, lean, and healthy.</p>

      <p><strong>Does water weight matter?</strong><br>
      A little. For best results, measure under similar conditions, ideally in the morning before meals.</p>

      <p><strong>Can bodybuilders use this?</strong><br>
      Yes. It‚Äôs a helpful tracker during bulking and cutting phases ‚Äî more accurate than BMI alone.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="back-link">
      <a href="/">‚Üê Back to All Calculators</a>
    </div>
  </div>

  <script is:client="load">
    const genderSelect = document.getElementById("gender");
    const hipInput = document.getElementById("hip");
    const hipLabel = document.getElementById("hipLabel");

    genderSelect.addEventListener("change", () => {
      if (genderSelect.value === "female") {
        hipInput.style.display = "block";
        hipLabel.style.display = "block";
      } else {
        hipInput.style.display = "none";
        hipLabel.style.display = "none";
      }
    });

    function calculateBodyFat() {
      const gender = document.getElementById("gender").value;
      const height = parseFloat(document.getElementById("height").value);
      const neck = parseFloat(document.getElementById("neck").value);
      const waist = parseFloat(document.getElementById("waist").value);
      const hip = parseFloat(document.getElementById("hip").value);
      const result = document.getElementById("bfResult");

      if (!height || !neck || !waist || (gender === "female" && !hip)) {
        result.textContent = "‚ö†Ô∏è Please fill in all required fields.";
        return;
      }

      let bodyFat;
      if (gender === "male") {
        bodyFat = 86.010 * Math.log10(waist - neck) - 70.041 * Math.log10(height) + 36.76;
      } else {
        bodyFat = 163.205 * Math.log10(waist + hip - neck) - 97.684 * Math.log10(height) - 78.387;
      }

      result.textContent = `Estimated Body Fat: ${bodyFat.toFixed(1)}%`;
    }
  </script>
